        moveline="...exd5 5.Ngf3 Nc6 6.Bb5 Bd6 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.O-O Nge7")
B.mv("9.Nb3 Bd6 (9...Bb6 10.Re1+ is also pleasant) 10.Bg5",
     "Bg5 pins and pressures; combined with Nb3 you are ready to plant a knight on d4. Note how every White piece "
     "points at the centre and the d-file.")
B.board("r1bqk2r/pp2nppp/2nb4/1B1p2B1/8/1N3N2/PPP2PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 5 10",
        "After 10.Bg5. The blockade of d4 is coming; the d5-pawn is the long-term target.",
        moveline="...8.O-O Nge7 9.Nb3 Bd6 10.Bg5")
B.sec("The blockade in action")
B.para("The single most important idea against an isolated pawn is to put a knight on the square directly in front "
       "of it - here, d4. From d4 the knight cannot be chased by pawns, it dominates the board, and it fixes the d5 "
       "pawn as a permanent weakness. A typical route is Nb3-d4 (or Nf3-d4):")
B.mv("...Nb3 Bb6 ... Nbd4  (the knight reaches its dream square)",
     "Once a knight sits on d4, you trade Black's active pieces around it, keep the d5-pawn fixed, and slowly pile "
     "up against it. The position below shows the blockade achieved.")
B.board("r1bqk2r/pp2nppp/1bn5/1B1p4/3N4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 10",
        "The blockade achieved: a White knight is immovable on d4, strangling the d5-pawn.",
        moveline="...Nb3 Bb6 ...Nbd4 (knight to the blockade square)")
B.sec("How White plays against the isolani - the three-step plan")
B.numbered([
 "BLOCKADE the pawn. Put a knight on d4. This is the single most important idea against an IQP - do it before "
 "anything else.",
 "TRADE pieces, especially minor pieces and a pair of rooks. The isolated pawn is a dynamic asset in the middlegame "
 "(it gives Black active pieces and the e4/c4 outposts) but a static weakness in the endgame. Every trade brings "
 "the endgame - and the weakness - closer.",
 "WIN the pawn or the square in front of it. With pieces off, double rooks on the d-file, add the queen, and invade "
 "the weak light squares. Often Black must surrender the pawn or accept a miserable, passive defence.",
])
B.sub("Black's other tries at move 6")
B.bullets([
 "6...Qe7+: a check to disrupt you. Simply 7.Be2 (blocking and keeping the bishop) leaves you comfortable; the "
 "queen is misplaced on e7 and you continue O-O, Nb3 and the blockade.",
 "6...Bd7: solid development that unpins by offering a trade on c6. You can keep the tension or take on c6 to "
 "damage the structure (see below); either way the d5-pawn remains the story.",
 "6...cxd4: giving up the c-pawn at once. Recapture and head for the same blockade plan - Black has simply chosen "
 "the isolani by a different move order.",
])
B.sub("The Bxc6 idea - changing the target")
B.para("Instead of the pure blockade you can play Bxc6 at the right moment. After ...bxc6 Black gets doubled, "
       "weak c-pawns and a half-open b-file for you to work against; after ...Nxc6 the structure stays an isolani "
       "but Black has lost a tempo and a defender. Choose based on the position: if Black's pieces are active, "
       "damaging the pawns with Bxc6 and trading down is often the cleaner path to a better endgame.")
B.sec("What you must NOT do")
B.bullets([
 "Do not let Black free the pawn with ...d4. If Black ever achieves ...d5-d4 safely, the isolani becomes a strong "
 "passed pawn and Black's pieces spring to life. Keep d4 firmly blockaded.",
 "Do not avoid trades hoping to attack. Against the IQP, simplification is your friend - the opposite of your usual "
 "instinct. Trade pieces, keep the pawn fixed, and let the endgame do the work.",
 "Do not rush. The isolani rarely falls by force; it falls to patience. Improve your pieces, hold the blockade, and "
 "Black's defence slowly cracks.",
])
B.callout("What to remember in the ...exd5 IQP line",
 "4.exd5 exd5 5.Ngf3 Nc6 6.Bb5, then dxc5 to leave Black a clean isolani. Blockade d4 with a knight, trade pieces, "
 "and grind - or use Bxc6 to damage the structure. This is the chapter where you practise the patience the rest of "
 "your chess needs.")

# ============================== PART III
B.part("PART III","The Closed Tarrasch: 3...Nf6")

B.chapter(4,"3...Nf6 4.e5 - The Main Closed Lines","The big pawn chain, and the fight for d4.")
B.para("3...Nf6 is Black's other main move. You grab space with 4.e5, kicking the knight and building the classic "
       "French chain: pawns on d4 and e5 versus Black's on d5 and e6. The whole struggle is about that chain - Black "
       "attacks its base (d4) with ...c5 and ...f6; you defend it and seek play on the kingside and the central files.")
B.mv("1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Bd3 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ne2",
     "The main tabiya. The moves work together: Bd3 eyes the kingside, c3 props up d4, and 7.Ne2 (the g1-knight!) "
     "is the key idea - it leaves the d2-knight in place as a SECOND defender of d4, keeps the f-pawn free for a "
     "later f4, and reroutes toward f4 or g3. Note: the d2-knight cannot reach e2, so 7.Ne2 is always Ng1-e2.")
B.board("r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2PB4/PP1NNPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 7",
        "The Closed Tarrasch main tabiya after 7.Ne2. Both White knights (d2 and e2) guard d4.",
        moveline="3...Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Bd3 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ne2")
B.sec("Black's main plan: the ...f6 break")
B.para("Black's most principled try is to undermine the chain at its head with ...f6. A typical sequence:")
B.mv("7...cxd4 8.cxd4 f6 9.exf6 Nxf6",
     "The chain dissolves and both sides are left with an isolated d-pawn. Now the d2-knight comes to f3 and you "
     "castle:")
B.board("r1bqkb1r/pp4pp/2n1pn2/3p4/3P4/3B4/PP1NNPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 10",
        "After 9...Nxf6. The chain is gone; play revolves around the e-file and the e5-square.",
        moveline="7...cxd4 8.cxd4 f6 9.exf6 Nxf6 (now 10.Nf3)")
B.mv("10.Nf3 Bd6 11.O-O O-O 12.Bf4",
     "A harmonious set-up. You contest the dark squares and the e5-outpost with Bf4 (offering to trade Black's "
     "good bishop), occupy the e-file with Re1, and aim a knight at e5. The chances are balanced but the position is "
     "easy and pleasant for White to play.")
B.board("r1bq1rk1/pp4pp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P1B2/3B1N2/PP2NPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 5 12",
        "After 12.Bf4. White fights for e5 and the e-file; both sides have an isolated d-pawn.",
        moveline="...9...Nxf6 10.Nf3 Bd6 11.O-O O-O 12.Bf4")
B.sec("Black's other try: ...Qb6 hitting d4 and b2")
B.para("Instead of ...f6, Black often plays ...Qb6, piling on d4 and eyeing b2. The standard handling:")
B.mv("7...Qb6 8.Nf3","Defending d4 with a second piece. The b2-pawn is poisoned - grabbing it opens lines toward "
     "the black queen and loses time. And a key tactical point:")
B.callout("The d4-pawn is defended TWICE - do not fear the grab",
 "After ...cxd4 cxd4, the d4-pawn is guarded by BOTH knights (f3 and e2). So Black's natural-looking "
 "...Ncxd4, ...Qxd4 fails outright: ...Nxd4, Nxd4, Qxd4?? simply drops the queen to the SECOND knight, Nxd4. "
 "(Old books show a flashy Bb5+ here, but with Black's knight sitting on d7 the bishop check is blocked - the real "
 "refutation is just the second recapture.) The practical lesson: keep d4 defended twice and let Black overreach.")
B.sec("If Black keeps it closed: your kingside expansion")
B.para("If Black delays the break and just manoeuvres (for example ...Be7, ...O-O, ...Qb6, ...Rc8), you turn your "
       "extra space into a kingside initiative. A model set-up:")
B.mv("7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.f4",
     "With the chain secured you advance on the kingside. The plan is f4-f5 to open lines at Black's king, often "
     "supported by Ne2-g3 (hitting f5 and h5) and sometimes h4-h5.")
B.board("r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2PB4/PP1NN1PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9",
        "After 9.f4. The chain is reinforced and White expands toward f5 on the kingside.",
        moveline="7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.f4 (heading for f5)")
B.bullets([
 "Piece routes to know: the e2-knight goes to g3 (eyeing f5 and h5); the d2-knight goes to f3 to bolster e5 and d4; "
 "the bishop sits on d3 aiming at h7.",
 "Meet Black's queenside play (...a5, ...b5, ...c4) by keeping pieces active rather than allowing a bind; if ...c4 "
 "hits your bishop, retreat to c2 where it still rakes the b1-h7 diagonal toward Black's king.",
 "Never let d4 collapse. The base of the chain is the hinge of the whole position - if it holds, your space "
 "advantage gives you the easier game.",
])
B.sub("Sharp option: the Tarrasch pawn-sacrifice")
B.para("In some lines (after an early ...cxd4 cxd4 and ...Qb6 or ...Nb6 hitting d4), White can choose to give up "
       "the d4-pawn for fast development and the initiative - the so-called Tarrasch gambit. It is a respected, "
       "aggressive try that may suit your attacking style; treat it as an advanced option once the main plans feel "
       "natural, and only with concrete preparation.")
B.callout("What to remember in the Closed Tarrasch",
 "4.e5 builds the chain; 5.Bd3, 6.c3, 7.Ne2 (g1-knight) is your set-up, with BOTH knights guarding d4. Meet ...f6 "
 "with exf6 and fight for e5; if Black sits tight, expand with f4-f5. Remember one square above all: d4.")

# ============================== PART IV
B.part("PART IV","The Flexible & The Rare")

B.chapter(5,"3...Be7 - The Universal System","Black keeps options open. You keep your space.")
B.para("3...Be7 is a flexible, modern move (a favourite of Morozevich). Black delays committing the knight and "
       "intends ...Nf6, ...c5 and sometimes a quick ...g5 against your chain. The good news: you meet it with natural "
       "development and usually transpose into a familiar closed structure with an extra tempo of clarity.")
B.mv("1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 Be7 4.Ngf3 Nf6 5.e5 Nfd7 6.c3 c5 7.Bd3 Nc6 8.O-O",
     "A pleasant closed Tarrasch. Because Black spent a move on ...Be7 rather than striking faster, you are "
     "comfortably developed and castled, with the same d4/e5 chain to play with. (Here the g1-knight has gone to f3, "
     "the natural square in this move order.)")
B.board("r1bqk2r/pp1nbppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2PB1N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8",
        "After 8.O-O in the 3...Be7 system. A comfortable closed Tarrasch with White fully mobilised.",
        moveline="3...Be7 4.Ngf3 Nf6 5.e5 Nfd7 6.c3 c5 7.Bd3 Nc6 8.O-O")
B.sec("If Black goes for the ...g5 thrust")
B.para("The independent point of 3...Be7 is that Black may try ...g5, hitting your chain and grabbing kingside "
       "space (sometimes with ...h5 too). Do not panic - meet flank aggression with calm and with the centre:")
B.bullets([
 "Keep your centre solid (the d4/e5 chain) and your king safe; an unprepared ...g5 weakens Black's own king as much "
 "as it attacks yours.",
 "Useful responses include h3 (to question ...g4), Nb3 and a timely dxc5, and central/queenside play to open lines "
 "while Black's kingside pawns are committed.",
 "Remember the rule: meet a wing attack with a counter-strike in the centre. If Black storms the kingside, look "
 "hard at dxc5 and opening the central files.",
])
B.para("A second independent plan is ...b6 and ...Ba6 to trade off your good light-squared bishop; meet it by "
       "keeping the bishop active (Bc2-b1 ideas) or accepting the trade when your remaining pieces are the better "
       "ones. Note also 4.Bd3 as a valid move-order alternative to 4.Ngf3 if you prefer to commit the bishop first.")
B.callout("What to remember against 3...Be7",
 "Develop naturally with 4.Ngf3 and steer into a closed Tarrasch; you will usually be a half-step ahead. If Black "
 "lunges with ...g5, stay calm, keep the centre, and hit back in the middle.")

B.chapter(6,"Everything Else","The rarer third moves - solved cleanly.")
B.para("Black has several minor third moves. None should trouble you if you know the simple, principled answer to "
       "each. The common thread: develop sensibly, keep your centre, and head for one of your three structures.")
B.sec("3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 - giving up the centre")
B.para("Black surrenders the centre to simplify. You recapture and enjoy a free, spacious game.")
B.bullets([
 "4...Nd7 (the Smyslov set-up, heading for ...Ngf6): 5.Nf3 Ngf6 6.Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.Bd3 with an easy space edge.",
 "4...Be7 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Bd3: simple development, comfortable for White.",
 "4...Nf6 5.Nxf6+ (Qxf6 or gxf6): trade and play against Black's slightly compromised structure.",
])
B.sub("The Fort Knox: 4...Bd7 and ...Bc6")
B.para("A solid, fashionable defensive set-up: Black trades the light-squared bishop, the French problem piece, via "
       "...Bd7-c6.")
B.mv("3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bd7 5.Nf3 Bc6 6.Bd3 Nd7 7.O-O",
     "Black is rock-solid but passive. You hold a small, risk-free pull: more space and freer pieces. Play Qe2, "
     "Rd1/Re1, c3-c4 or Ng3, and probe patiently - there is nothing for Black to attack and a lot for you to press.")
B.board("r2qkbnr/pppn1ppp/2b1p3/8/3PN3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 6 7",
        "The Fort Knox after 7.O-O. Solid for Black, but White has lasting space and the easier game.",
        moveline="3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bd7 5.Nf3 Bc6 6.Bd3 Nd7 7.O-O")
B.sec("The other rare moves")
B.bullets([
 "3...a6: prepares ...c5 and ...b5 without allowing Bb5. Just develop - 4.Ngf3 c5 5.exd5 (your main structures) or "
 "5.c3. Treat it as a slightly slow 3...c5.",
 "3...Nc6: blocks Black's own ...c5. Play 4.Ngf3 (or 4.c3) and develop comfortably - Black has given up his best "
 "break.",
 "3...c4: grabbing queenside space and releasing the central tension. This helps you: the centre is now stable, so "
 "play b3 to undermine c4, or simply develop and prepare e5 and f4 with a free hand in the centre.",
 "3...b6: a fianchetto to defend d5 and pressure e4. Develop Ngf3, Bd3 (or Be2), c3, O-O; your space and central "
 "majority give a comfortable game.",
 "3...f5: ambitious but loosening. 4.exf5 (or supporting the centre) exploits the holes ...f5 leaves; develop and "
 "target the light squares.",
 "3...h6: a slow move that does little. Develop normally - Ngf3, Bd3, c3, O-O - and you are simply better developed.",
])
B.callout("The universal answer to a rare move",
 "If you ever face a third move not in your notes: defend e4 if needed, play Ngf3 and Bd3, support d4 with c3, "
 "castle, and ask which of the three structures you are in. The plan follows from the structure. That is the whole "
 "Tarrasch.")

# ============================== PART V
B.part("PART V","Understanding & Training")

B.chapter(7,"The Three Structures: A Strategy Handbook","Plans, breaks and piece routes - the heart of it.")
B.para("Openings are won and lost in the middlegames they produce. Here is the strategic essence of each of your "
       "three structures, in the form you can use at the board.")
B.sec("Structure 1 - The development lead (from 4...Qxd5)")
B.bullets([
 "Your assets: faster development, open central files, a slightly exposed black queen and king.",
 "Plan: Re1 and Qe2 for the e-file, Bg5/Bf4 and Rad1, with Nb5/Ne5 ideas; create threats before Black completes "
 "development.",
 "The break to prevent: Black's ...e5. Stay active so ...Be7, ...O-O and ...e5 never come together safely.",
])
B.sec("Structure 2 - The isolated queen's pawn (from 4...exd5)")
B.bullets([
 "Your assets: a permanent target on d5 and the strong blockade square d4.",
 "Plan: knight to d4, trade minor pieces and a pair of rooks, then win the pawn or the d5-square in the endgame. Or "
 "play Bxc6 to damage the structure when Black's pieces are active.",
 "Golden rule: with an IQP on the board, the side playing AGAINST it wants to trade pieces; the side WITH it wants "
 "to attack. You are against it - so trade.",
 "The break to prevent: Black's ...d4. Keep the pawn blockaded and it stays a weakness forever.",
])
B.sec("Structure 3 - The closed chain (from 3...Nf6 4.e5)")
B.bullets([
 "Your assets: more space and the d4/e5 chain cramping Black.",
 "Plan: defend d4 twice (c3, plus knights on d2 and e2), develop, then expand on the kingside with f4-f5, or "
 "manoeuvre Ne2-g3 toward f5/h5; the d2-knight reroutes to f3 to bolster e5.",
 "Breaks: meet Black's ...f6 with exf6 and fight for e5; prepare your own f4-f5. Respect ...c5/...cxd4 pressure on "
 "d4 and queenside expansion with ...a5-...b5-...c4 (answer ...c4 with Bc2, keeping the attacking diagonal).",
])
B.callout("Pawn breaks decide everything",
 "In each structure one break matters most. Development-lead: yours on the e-file, and stopping Black's ...e5. IQP: "
 "stopping Black's ...d4 while you pressure d5. Closed: meeting Black's ...f6 and preparing your f4-f5. Know the "
 "break, and you know the plan.")

B.chapter(8,"Traps, Pitfalls & Your Study Plan","Knowing the dangers, and learning the lines efficiently.")
B.sec("The d4-pawn 'trap' in the closed lines - the truth")
B.para("The most important tactical point in the closed Tarrasch is also the most misunderstood. When Black piles on "
       "d4 with ...Qb6 and ...Nc6 and then tries to win it by force - ...cxd4, cxd4, ...Ncxd4, ...Qxd4 - the grab "
       "simply fails, because after 7.Ne2 your d4-pawn is defended by BOTH knights. Once one knight recaptures, the "
       "OTHER one takes the queen. (You may have seen this 'trap' presented with a flashy Bb5+; in the actual "
       "position Black's knight on d7 blocks that check, so the real and complete refutation is just the second "
       "recapture.) The practical lesson for you: keep d4 defended twice, never panic about ...Qb6, and let Black "
       "overextend.")
B.sec("Pitfalls to avoid as White")
B.bullets([
 "In the IQP lines, do not get talked out of trading. Your attacker's instinct says 'keep pieces on'; against an "
 "isolani that instinct is wrong. Trade and grind.",
 "In the closed lines, never let d4 fall cheaply - if it goes, your space advantage usually goes with it.",
 "In the ...Qxd5 lines, do not waste your development lead chasing pawns. Tempo and activity are the point.",
 "Castle and finish development before launching anything. Even with a space edge, a loose king invites the "
 "counterattack.",
])
B.sec("How to learn this repertoire in four weeks")
B.numbered([
 "Week 1 - the IQP (Chapter 3). The most instructive structure and the one you meet most against good players. Play "
 "ten games steering for 4...exd5 positions; drill the blockade-and-trade plan.",
 "Week 2 - the closed lines (Chapter 4). Learn the 7.Ne2 tabiya, the ...f6 break and the f4-f5 plan cold. Play ten "
 "games in the chain.",
 "Week 3 - the ...Qxd5 development-lead lines (Chapter 2) and 3...Be7 (Chapter 5). Lighter theory; focus on fast, "
 "active development.",
 "Week 4 - the rare moves (Chapter 6) and a full review. Re-read the strategy handbook, then play a mixed set and "
 "check every French against your notes.",
])
B.callout("Build it into a database",
 "Create a study (on Lichess or in a PGN) with one chapter per structure. After every French you play, drop the "
 "game into the right chapter and note where you or your opponent left the plan. Within a month this repertoire "
 "will feel like home, and the French will become one of your favourite things to see on the board.")

